<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-317  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 317.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Jan 9 1989 v8 n1 p86(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bush told of IRM pay gap problem. (George Bush; informationresource management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Accounting OfficeReportsSalaryGovernment OfficialsInformation Resources ManagementPersonnel Problems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Bush Told of IRM Pay Gap ProblemandM;The General Accounting Office has let the Bush transition team in on awell-known secret: Federal agencies cannot attract trained technicalmanagers, and that fact is hindering some major ADP projects.andM;&quot;Rapid turnover of leadership, resulting in several changes in direction, andinsufficient technical leadership and staff were seriously impairing theSocial Security Administration's and the Internal Revenue Service's effortsto modernize their computer systems,&quot; GAO concluded in one of several reportsprepared for the presidential transition.andM;&quot;You get what you pay for,&quot; GAO said.andP;  &quot;Unfortunately, the federalgovernment's pay structure has broken down.&quot;andM;GAO said the government should rethink its pay systems and focus on improvingthe situation rather than defending current programs.andP;  The problem, accordingto GAO, goes beyond pay, which lags seriously behind industry, especially forADP and IRM professionals.andM;It recommended three steps that numerous officials and think tanks alreadyhave proposed as a foundation for achieving a better public service: Thepresident must support the public service.andP;  New political employees shouldadhere to rigorous ethical standards.andM;And the benefits and pay structure for political and career employees must berevamped.andO;</TEXT></DOC>